Defendant Emmanuel O Norton in court with attorney Cheryl Anne Ward.  Defendant Emmanuel O Norton in custody.  Thomas L. Potter appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant changes plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon he may no longer use or possess any firearms; also he may not vote in any election until his civil rights have been restored.  Court further advised that if he is not a US citizen, deportation is possible. 

 Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, Defense and Defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:

The Court sentenced defendant to serve 10  MONTHS in the House of Corrections, FIRST 4 MONTHS STRAIGHT TIME, and LAST 6 MONTHS release to the Day Reporting Center, with credit for 78 days time served.  

-Court ordered defendant pay Court costs and all applicable surcharges and assessments during term of probation on COUNT 2; nonpayment penalty shall result in a civil judgment
-Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the related surcharge during term of probation on COUNT 2; nonpayment penalty shall result in a civil judgment

AS TO COUNT 2:
The Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 4 YEARS.  INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 2 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 2 YEARS, consecutive to COUNT 1.  Court STAYED sentence and placed the defendant on PROBATION for a period of 3 YEARS with the following conditions for probation and extended supervision:
Defendant is for the Challenge Incarceration Program and is eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program. 
-Defendant to pay Court costs and all applicable surcharges and assessments to be collected during term probation.  If defendant is revoked, all applicable surcharges and assessments are to be collected by DOC from up to 25% of prison funds. Nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment
-Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the related surcharge to be collected during term of probation. If defendant is revoked, all related surcharges are to be collected by DOC from up to 25% of prison funds; nonpayment penalty shall result in a civil judgment
-No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
-Cooperate with agent
-Cooperate with any correctional programs recommended
-Follow all rules of probation and extended supervision
-Pay all supervision fees 
-Obtain/maintain full-time employment 
-Obtain GED or HSED
-AODA assessment and any recommended treatment
-Absolute sobriety with random urine screens and breathalyzers
-No alcohol or illegal drugs 
-No use of prescription drugs without a valid prescription 
-Defendant to perform 50 hours of community service
-Court does not allow for expungement
